Dear Mr. Fox:

Your email to the Governor's office was referred to me for response. I checked with the NCDOT Alexander County maintenance office for the background on Jake Reese Court.

The paving project went on the list for paving priority sometime in 2001, with several projects above it in priority. Right of Way (R/W) research began in early 2004 only to have a conflict with an out of state property owner. This person did not want to sign the proposed R/W agreement, which was required to go through with the paving, and attempts to contact this person to negotiate an agreement were unsuccessful. The budget crunch in 2005-06 put a lot of secondary construction programs on hold, adding to the delay. In the meantime, efforts to negotiate a R/W agreement with the out of state property owner continued to be held up as we went in to 2007 without a response to any method of contact. Finally the remaining property owners agreed to fund the Secondary Roads Condemnation process, and in mid-2008, the NCDOT district office in Statesville began the initial surveys. Once completed, the R/W department in Shelby sent a letter to the out of state property owner to explain the upcoming condemnation procedure, and only then did she contact the NCDOT district engineer that oversees Alexander County. This person has since signed the R/W agreement and it was recorded on Oct. 28, 2008. Now that all R/W agreements have been signed, we are at the mercy of the current budget situation. Once it improves and money is available for the project, Jake Reese Court is number one on the list to be graded and paved. If you need additional information, please contact NCDOT Alexander County Maintenance Engineer Cole G. Gurley at (828-632-2164).

Sincerely yours,

Steve Abbott
NCDOT Communications Officer


