Dear Mr. Grierson:



I have been asked by the Governor’s Office to respond.  Thank you for writing and sharing your concern about roadside litter.



North Carolina does a have a litter problem.  During the winter months, litter becomes more prevalent due to the weather and the ability for litter removal crews to get out.  It is the responsibility of the N.C. Department of Transportation to maintain the 79,000 miles of roadways in our state, and this includes litter removal.



The NCDOT has an ongoing agreement with the N.C. Department of Correction to utilize inmate squads for statewide roadside litter removal.  Each year the NCDOT spends more than $16 million to remove more than 10 million pounds of roadside litter.



The NCDOT also works with non profit organizations as N.C. Keep America Beautiful and N.C. Big Sweep.  Their volunteers participate in litter cleanups and remove up to another million pounds of litter annually.



In addition to the NCDOT Adopt-A-Highway groups and other volunteers, those in the Community Service Work Program also participate in litter removal during the NCDOT Litter Sweep – the department’s biannual statewide roadside litter cleanup.  Litter Sweep is held the last two weeks of April and September.  All citizens can participate.



The state’s Litter Law (G.S. 14-399) has fines from $250 up to $2,000, a point on the driver license and community service for those convicted.  Annually there are more than 5,500 litter and unsecured load citations issued.



Mr. Grierson, I invite you to visit the NCDOT Office of Beautification Programs Web site to learn more about the various litter prevention initiatives at <http://www.ncdot.org/doh/operations/dp_chief_eng/roadside/Beautification/> www.ncdot.org/~/Beautification.  Once at this location you will find many links, i.e. Litter Law, Adopt-A-Highway and Swat-A-Litterbug programs, Litter Sweep, school curriculums within Litter Prevention, and the state’s litter report within “News.”



In closing, I want to provide you the phone number of the local NCDOT  Guilford County maintenance office where you can report the heavily littered sites or roadway hazards.  The person answering the phone will take your information and then take the appropriate action.  The phone number is 336-668-2424.



Thank you again for writing.  We know there is more to do.  I hope the information I’ve provided is helpful.



Sincerely,



George Kapetanakis



