The NCDOT has a biannual litter cleanup called Litter Sweep where its employees, Adopt-A-Highway groups, NC DOC inmate squads, those in Community Service Work and other citizen volunteers will pick up roadside litter.  Litter Sweep is normally held the last two weeks of April and September.  The cleanup will usually remove more than two million pounds of roadside litter during each Litter Sweep.



When it comes to the State of North Carolina litter law, it has fines from $250 up to $2,000 and can be doubled with subsequent convictions.  A point on the driver license and community service work can also be part of the penalty.  Citations for littering can include intentional and unintentional littering as well as for unsecured loads.  Court costs are added to the fine.



