From:                           Angela M. Faulk. NCDOT Human Resources Director



Subject:                        NCDOT Positions and Responsibilities



Date:                            February 20, 2009





Dear Mr. Gioscio:



This is in response to an e-mail we received on information you sent to the Office of the Governor on Tuesday, February 17, 2009 relating to NCDOT positions and responsibilities.  The positions that were referred to in the e-mail are assigned to the central Construction Unit.  Due to increases in duties and responsibilities, these positions (Transportation Engineer IIIs SG 78) were studied in July 2008 for a reclassification. Based on results from the review, the positions were reallocated up to Transportation Staff Engineer (TSE) IVs (SG 80). When the TSE IVs were crosswalked during the career banding conversion in November 2008, they were placed at the Engineer Advanced level.  This is the same level as the TE IIIs.



The duties and responsibilities of the TSE IVs are very different from the Transportation Engineering Supervisor (TES) IIs (Resident Engineers) (SG 79).  These positions serve as technical experts for critical construction operations contracts that affect final quality as well as new or unique construction methods for all division let and centrally let highway construction projects.  They provide formal and informal training to project engineering and inspection staff to ensure all construction details are properly monitored.  The Bridge and Roadway Construction Engineers (TSE IVs) have a thorough understanding of the Unit’s construction program, as well as a global understanding and working knowledge of the Department.  They serve as regional project managers and are charged with ensuring timely program delivery.



As regional project managers, these TSE IV positions are assigned responsibility (either bridge or roadway) for overseeing two Divisions. They are responsible for making decisions within the two Division areas (Bridge or Roadway) that each is assigned.  Sometimes these decisions involve overriding the TES IIs (Resident Engineers) in the field.  These positions review all supplemental agreements, active claims, moderate Construction Close-Out Conferences between Contractors and Division Staff.  Their duties are much more complex as it relates to variety and complexity, decision making/consequence of error, and analytical requirements due to the exposure they have within their assigned two Divisions. They are essentially on the “front line” conducting daily business, having to make decisions whose effects are felt within the assigned area related to the construction projects.



Typically from two to six TES IIs are assigned within each of the fourteen Divisions’ Construction areas.  The TES IIs were crosswalked over to the Engineering Supervisor Journey level.  These supervisors, depending on location, typically manage from one to two squads.  These squads usually consist of one or two lower level Engineers and varying levels of Engineering Technicians.  These supervisors spend a considerable amount of time performing the more complex, controversial or advanced work of their squads.  These positions are only responsible for their squads’ construction projects.  Their classification and level is driven by the supervision they perform and the complexity of their duties and responsibilities. Were it not for this supervision, they would be classified as Transportation Engineer IIs or the banded classification of Engineer – Journey not Engineering Supervisor – Journey. 



The Bridge and Roadway Construction Engineers have multiple assigned areas and have responsibility over those areas as it relates to bridges and roadway projects.  These positions have the authority to override a Resident Engineer’s decision but the opposite is not the case.  These positions are considered the highest level of technical staff work involved in engineering oriented problem solving.  It is for these reasons, the positions were reallocated up back in July 2008 and are more complex than the Division Construction Transportation Engineering Supervisor II.




