As you mention, the NCDOT contract language includes a 12-month guarantee provision. This provision requires that the contractor guarantee materials and workmanship against latent and patent defects arising from faulty materials, faulty workmanship or negligence for a period of 12 months following the date of final acceptance of the project. 

Concerning responsibility for the quality of work that has been done, a team of engineers reviews each project at approximately 10 months after the its acceptance date to determine if the guarantee provision needs to be invoked on a contract. If items of work which necessitate invoking the provision are found, a letter is sent to the contractor to make the necessary repairs. The same engineering team also completes a construction quality evaluation form, rating various components of the project and identifying specific improvements to avoid future occurrences. In addition, contractors who are awarded NCDOT construction projects are required to submit a contract payment bond and a contract performance bond each in an amount equal to 100 percent of the amount of the contract.
To further hold ourselves accountable for the work being done, the Department has developed budget and schedule metrics, and each project is evaluated upon completion to determine if the target metric is achieved. The Project Managers' performance is evaluated on those established metrics.
As for holding a contractor responsible for its work over a longer period of time, there are three trial projects where the guarantee was extended to three years for pavements. The Department is continuing to evaluate the use of extended project guarantees.

